     "], {{0, 307.5}, {570.5, 0}}, {0, 255},
     ColorFunction->RGBColor,
     ImageResolution->144],
    BoxForm`ImageTag["Byte", ColorSpace -> "RGB", Interleaving -> True],
    Selectable->False],
   DefaultBaseStyle->"ImageGraphics",
   ImageSize->{422.89999999999975`, Automatic},
   ImageSizeRaw->{570.5, 307.5},
   PlotRange->{{0, 570.5}, {0, 307.5}}]], "Input",ExpressionUUID->
  "85f761a5-55c3-4ec9-b87f-1d795fc272e4"],
 "\n\nWe need a criterion to stop the partitioning of the data. A typical \
criterion consists in stopping when a new partition does not decrease the \
loss function more than a certain value (set by us). Alternatively, we can \
stop when the number of partitions reaches a maximum (also set by us).\n\n\
Here, I have focused on data with a single feature (i.e. 1-dimensional data). \
These methods, however, can be generalised to data with multiple features. \n\
\nIf interested, see more information in (not required for the course):\n\n\
Chapter 14 of Jeremy Watt, Reza Borhani, Aggelos K. Katsaggelos \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Machine Learning Refined: Foundations, Algorithms, and \
Applications\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] Cambridge University Press, 2nd Edition \
(2020).\n\nChapter 16 of Kevin P. Murphy \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Machine \
Learning: A Probabilistic Perspective\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] The MIT Press \
(2012)."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7814549111713023`*^9, 3.781454961122964*^9}, 
